{{Infobox planet | minorplanet = yes | background = #FFC2E0 | name = {{mp|2008 HJ}} | image = | caption = | discovery_ref = | discoverer = [[Lincoln Near-Earth Asteroid Research|LINEAR]] | discovery_site = [[Lincoln Laboratory's ETS|Lincoln Lab ETS]] | discovered = 24 April 2008 | mpc_name = {{mp|2008 HJ|}} | mp_category = [[Near-Earth object|NEO]]{{·}}[[Apollo asteroid|Apollo]]&thinsp;<ref name=jpldata/> | orbit_ref = &thinsp;<ref name=jpldata/> | epoch = 13 January 2016 ([[Julian day|JD]] 2457400.5) | aphelion = {{Convert|2.29553|AU|Gm|abbr=on|lk=on}} (Q) | perihelion = {{Convert|0.968318|AU|Gm|abbr=on}} (q) | semimajor = {{Convert|1.63192|AU|Gm|abbr=on}} (a) | eccentricity = 0.40664 (e) | period = 2.08 [[Julian year (astronomy)|yr]] (761.46 [[Julian year (astronomy)|d]]) | mean_anomaly = 237.912[[Degree (angle)|°]] (M) | inclination = 0.925579° (i) | asc_node = 47.4700° (Ω) | arg_peri = 204.1346° (ω) | dimensions = 12×24 m | mass = 5×10<sup>6</sup> kg (assumed) | albedo = | spectral_type = | sidereal_day = {{Convert|0.01185|h|s|abbr=on|lk=on|disp=flip}} | abs_magnitude = 25.8<ref name=jpldata/> | mean_motion = {{Deg2DMS|0.472775|sup=ms}} /day (n) | uncertainty = 6 | moid = {{Convert|0.00170917|AU|km|abbr=on}} | jupiter_moid = {{Convert|2.75111|AU|Gm|abbr=on}} }}
'''2008 HJ''' is a sub-kilometer [[asteroid]], classified as [[near-Earth object]] of the [[Apollo asteroid|Apollo group]].
It was discovered by [[Lincoln Near-Earth Asteroid Research|Lincoln Laboratory ETS]], New Mexico. Observers M. Bezpalko, D. Torres, R. Kracke, G. Spitz, J. Kistler. [Richard Miles using the [[Faulkes Telescope South]] at [[Siding Spring Observatory]], [[Australia]] determined that the asteroid rotates rapidly. It measures only 12 m by 24 m and is very dense, having a mass of about 5,000 [[tonne]]s. If the asteroid were not dense, it is probable that the rapid rotation would cause the asteroid to disrupt and fly apart.
At the time of discovery, {{mp|2008 HJ}} had the smallest known [[period of revolution|rotation period]] in the [[Solar System]], completing one revolution every 42.7 seconds.<ref name=jpldata/><ref name=bbc/>
It is listed on the [[Sentry (monitoring system)|Sentry Risk Table]] with a 1 in 17,000 chance of [[Impact event|impacting]] Earth on May 2, 2081.<ref name=summary/> An impact from this object would be comparable to the [[Chelyabinsk meteor]].
==See also== *[[List of fast rotators (minor planets)]]
